Description: Small fragment of a seal-impression. The fine brown Nile clay with some mica inclusions was hardened after excavation. The rear shows a concave surface with plant fibres, probably wood impression like a bolt or the base of a knob with one or two string impressions running perpendicular to the wood. In the break the impression of a twisted string with a width of 0.25 cm. The front side is slightly convex and covered with finger-impressions. A small part of an oval scarab-like seal-impression with a circumferential line is preserved, inside two small upright cobras underneath each other running of a central circled line like a cartouche. Small traces of the last sign, but not identifiable anymore.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
